How can I show that $L_2\le L_1$ $||x||_1\ge ||x||_2$ and also we have that $\|x\|_2\leq \sqrt m\|x\|_{\infty}$ regarding the first part, can I say that: $$
\sqrt{\sum\limits_{i=1}^n x^2 } \leq {\sum\limits_{i=1}^n {\sqrt x}^2 }
$$

Prove the following identity: \begin{equation}
\left[\frac{d^{2n}}{dx^{2n}}e^{x^2/2a}\right]_{x=0}=\frac{(2n-1)!!}{a^n}
\end{equation} The final derivative must be evaluated at $x=0$.
